You could actually do this without a single change to the JSX transform, and instead just make a simple object that calls m() with the right params. Then you just change the @jsx pragma to point at that object. With a complete array of elements this should mostly work.<p>```js
/<i></i> @jsx m.dom */<p>function m(type, props, children) {
  // assuming m() looks something like this.
  return { type: type, props: props, children: children};
}
m.render = function(lwDOM){ console.log(lwDOM)};
m.dom = {};<p>// React hard codes this array so we can do something like this to build the mapping
[&#x27;a&#x27;, &#x27;span&#x27;].forEach((el) => { m.dom[el] = function(props, ...args) { return m.call(null, el, props, args); } });<p>m.render(
  <a href={&quot;google.com&quot;}>
    <span>hello</span>
    <span>world</span>
  </a>
);
```
